snippet.textDisplay: I called this over ten years ago back when Hulu first came out (which most people will forget was free at the time, no adds). People bashed the cable companies (and yes, you still need a land line phone people), but I always saw this for what was going to happen, cable companies charging extra for internet only packages as they own those services, then multiple players hording their own media in the streaming space, only this time instead of paying one person, you are forced to pay twice as much sending your money in multiple directions.  That's what is happening. And according to most than a few sources, the Disney boom was only temporary, with most subscriptions being temporary free ones.

snippet.textDisplay:
While this is not a popular belief, it's still true:

The core problem here is a government-supported monopoly-centric business model that keeps all other voluntarist-based business models so far away that most people think they don't even exist. The government-supported monopoly-centric business model?: Intellectual Property. The idea that you can own/control what OTHER people do with information they have. The idea that you can compel people to pay for things in a contract they never signed. Intellectual Property is indeed a business model, but an immoral one ...and if it disappeared we would get even GREATER content than what we have today. (Who still remembers the days of creativity on YouTube before they started cracking down on IP? ...creativity was all over the place... taking whatever existed and making it even better. But nowadays only 1 person/group can create and no one else can make it better without permission).
